"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802967","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>Health services are the responsibility of the Department of Health. Child refugees are entitled to the same rights as other looked-after children and young people, including access to National Health Service (NHS) mental health services. The NHS actively seeks to meet the unique needs of a wide range of vulnerable groups, including asylum seekers of all ages, and local NHS services have legal duties to meet the varied needs of their population. Access to Mental Health services is based on clinical need. To improve the offer to all children, the Government published The Children and Young People’s Mental Health Green Paper on 4 December. This sets out an ambitious set of proposals to transform support for children and young people’s mental health generally.</p><p>Refugee resettlement programmes can also provide an avenue towards mental healthcare. Under resettlement programmes, Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) and Local Health Boards can claim a per capita amount for primary and secondary healthcare costs – including mental health costs – for refugees they support. If per capita costs are exhausted, CCGs and Local Health Boards can claim additional funding for secondary healthcare costs identified during the first 12 months of a refugee's arrival. Funding decisions do not rest with the Department for Communities and Local Government but with the Home Office, which is accountable for the Resettlement Programme.</p><p>Local authorities have been invited to bid for funds to assist their capacity to support unaccompanied asylum-seeking children (UASC) through the Controlling Migration Fund. The Department for Communities and Local Government manages part of this fund, and bids have included interventions to support UASC mental health. The bidding opportunity has closed and we will be announcing the results of this programme early in the New Year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-18T17:58:26.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802967/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802967/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-08","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to support local authority provision of mental health services for child refugees.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","118387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802968","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>Child refugees are entitled to the same rights as other looked-after children and young people, including access to National Health Service mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS actively seeks to meet the unique needs of a wide range of vulnerable groups, including asylum seekers of all ages, and local NHS services have legal duties to meet the varied needs of their population.</p><p> </p><p>Access to mental health services is based on clinical need. To improve the offer to all children, the Government published the Children and Young People’s Mental Health Green Paper on 4 December. This sets out an ambitious set of proposals to transform support for children and young people’s mental health generally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-18T16:42:27.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802968/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802968/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Mental Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to address the mental health needs of child refugees.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","118388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802969","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-14","<p>I have raised the issue of refugee returns on several occasions with the Government of Lebanon, including during a visit to Lebanon in October 2017, where I met with President Michel Aoun and Prime Minister Saad Hariri, among others. I also discussed the issue with Education Minister Marwan Hamade and Foreign Minister Gebran Bassil when they visited the UK in November. The UK is committed to ensuring that any refugee returns to Syria take place voluntarily, in safety and dignity, in line with international law. We do not support forced returns and will not support any returns before Syria or parts of Syria are declared safe by the United Nations. United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees does not currently consider conditions to be in place for refugees to return to Syria in safety and dignity.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-14T17:39:49.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802969/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802969/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-08","Lebanon: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with her counterpart in the Lebanese Government on the potential forced return of refugees to Syria.","false","Biography information for George Freeman","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","118389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802970","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>We are consulting on how to implement the proposals set out in the Green Paper. Following consultation, the Department will make available funding to take forward the proposals, in addition to the existing funding available for children and young people’s mental health transformation. Details will follow in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-18T16:37:16.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802970/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802970/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to his Department's proposals in its Green Paper on children and young people's mental health, published on 4 December 2017, if he will set out the sources of the funding for those proposals.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","118390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802971","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>Additional funding for ‘Transforming Children and Young People’s mental health provision: a green paper’ will be made available following public consultation.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-18T16:36:15.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802971/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802971/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to his Department's proposals in its Green Paper on children and young people's mental health, published on 4 December 2017, whether the funding referred to is additional to money already allocated for mental health.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","118391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802972","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-18","<p>This information is not recorded centrally by HMPPS.</p><p> </p><p>Health is devolved in Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The HMP Berwyn project team, Welsh Government and Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board have worked closely together to assess the potential impact of HMP Berwyn on local health services, including emergency services. A full health needs assessment was carried out in the early stages of the development of the prison and models of care were developed from this.</p><p> </p><p>A full range of health and wellbeing services are available to the men at HMP Berwyn including primary care services, mental health and learning disability services, and services for men with a need for substance misuse treatment with the aim of reducing the local health impact as far as possible.</p><p> </p><p>These services are housed in a purpose built facility and are staffed by a variety of health and wellbeing professionals.</p><p> </p><p>Men who present with issues which may require attendance at hospital are assessed by health professionals before any decision is made to take them to hospital. There are a wide range of interventions which can be provided by the health and wellbeing team in situ to prevent the need for men to attend at local emergency departments.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-12-18T15:53:19.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802972/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802972/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-08","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the extra pressure on A&E services in north east Wales caused by treating prisoners from HMP Berwyn.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","118392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802973","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-14","<p>A full range of health and wellbeing services are available to the men at HMP Berwyn including primary care services, mental health and learning disability services, and services for men with a need for substance misuse services.</p><p> </p><p>These services are housed in purpose built facility and are staffed by a variety of health and wellbeing professionals.</p><p> </p><p>Health is devolved in Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Welsh Government, Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board and the HMP Berwyn project team have worked closely together to assess the potential impact of HMP Berwyn on local health services, including emergency services. A full health needs assessment was carried out in the early stages of the development of the prison and models of care were developed from this, with the aim of reducing the local health impact as far as possible.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-14T16:24:44.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802973/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802973/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-08","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of installing medical facilities at HMP Berwyn to reduce the pressure on local NHS providers.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","118393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802974","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Assessing the sustainability of its business models is the operational responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p>The Post Office’s Local business model allows the hosting businesses to improve their retail offer, by removing the need for a fortress counter to free up space in the shop to sell other items, and by integrating the post office counter into the main retail counter enabling efficiencies in running the store.</p><p>There are over 3,800 Local model post offices operating across the UK. Host retailers will also benefit from the associated footfall into the branch and Postmasters who have converted to the Local model have reported an average increase of 11% in their associated retail sales.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-13T14:17:39.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802974/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802974/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Post Offices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the sustainability of the Post Office Local business model in which postmasters are obliged to cover all business overheads but are not necessarily able to cover their employee’s wages.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802975","Home Office","false","2017-12-15","<p>It has been the practice of successive governments that we do not comment on specific cases.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","118297 ; 118298 ; 118299 ; 118300 ; 118303","2017-12-15T14:35:53.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802975/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802975/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-08","Freezing of Assets: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask The Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of using the powers given to him under of the Criminal Finances Act against those listed under the US Sergei Magnitsky Rule of Law Accountability Act of 2012.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","118395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802976","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-14","<p>Men who present with issues which may require attendance at hospital, short of emergency medical issues, are assessed by health professionals before any decision is made to take them to hospital. There are a wide range of interventions which can be provided by the health and wellbeing team in situ to prevent the need for men to attend at local emergency departments. In the event of a medical emergency a man may be transferred to local services if care cannot be provided within HMP Berwyn but men are transferred back to the prison at the earliest appropriate opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>A risk assessment will decide the level of staffing required for the safe transfer to hospital and during any further hospital stay. This will be completed before any move to hospital from HMP Berwyn except in an emergency. The risk assessment is approved by the Head of Security or the person operationally in charge of the prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-14T16:25:20.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802976/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802976/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-08","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the procedure is for taking an inmate from HMP Berwyn to local A&E services.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","118396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802977","Department of Health","false","2017-12-18","<p>NHS England does not issue national guidance on this matter. In England, it would be a matter for local clinical commissioning groups as commissioners of emergency care.</p><p> </p><p>In practice, a person would be triaged in the same way as any other person arriving at accident and emergency and would be seen on the basis of seriousness of their presentation. The fact they are brought in from a prison would have no bearing on their urgency at being seen, this would be solely down to their clinical presentation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-18T16:12:23.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802977/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802977/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Accident and Emergency Departments: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is his Department's policy for inmates to be seen immediately when they are taken to local A&E services.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","118397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802978","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Government has provided debt guarantees to support the provision of affordable and privately rented homes since 2013. The existing guarantee schemes have supported the delivery of over 42,000 homes.</p><p>The further £8 billion guarantee capacity will ensure that the housing sector continues to be able to the access debt markets once the existing guarantee schemes have expired.</p><p>We will engage the market over the coming months as to the most effective way of deploying this new guarantee capacity.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-18T12:03:52.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802978/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802978/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-08","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to Autumn Budget 2017, how the announced £8 billion of new guarantees to support house building will operate in practice.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","118398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802979","Department for Education","false","2017-12-18","<p>The department will publish criteria for the fund early next year. The fund will help to build construction training facilities attached to housing developments, and will support adult students to retrain as construction workers. We will welcome bids from colleges and developers from across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The funding for construction skills was announced in the Budget, as part of the National Retraining Scheme. Most of the funding will be a construction skills fund for England, which will support government’s ambition to build new homes during the Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>There will also be £5 million for construction skills in the West Midlands, as part of the second devolution deal.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-12-18T17:05:28.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802979/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802979/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-08","Construction: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to Autumn Budget 2017, what the criteria is for the allocation of the £34 million fund for teaching construction skills.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","118399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802980","Wales Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>Since the referendum I have been engaging with stakeholders throughout Wales to hear their views on how we make Brexit work for Wales, including through my expert panel of stakeholders. Many of the issues they have raised are common across the whole of the UK.</p><p>Where issues have been brought to my attention, the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales has worked with the Department for Exiting the European Union, and other Government departments, to fully consider these as part of achieving a deal that works for all parts of the United Kingdom.</p><p>I will continue to work with other Government departments, my expert panel of stakeholders, the Welsh Government, and the National Assembly for Wales, to support the Welsh economy and promote a prosperous Wales within a strong United Kingdom.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-12-13T13:12:22.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802980/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802980/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-12-08","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has identified any risks arising from the UK leaving the EU that are specific to Wales and the Welsh economy.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","118400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802981","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Artificial Intelligence (AI) and data analytics will change jobs and businesses across the country, and we want people to be able to capitalise on these opportunities. Following a review of AI led by Professor Dame Wendy Hall and Jérôme Pesenti,<em> Growing the AI Industry in the UK</em>, our Industrial Strategy will address the Grand Challenge of making the UK a global centre for AI and data innovation and embed the power of this technology across our economy.</p><p>Embedding AI across the UK will create thousands of good quality jobs and drive economic growth across the regions. A recent study found digital technologies created a net total of 80,000 new jobs annually across a population similar to the UK. By one estimate, AI could add £232bn to the UK economy by 2030.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-13T14:15:50.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802981/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802981/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Automation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will commission a formal assessment of the potential effect of automation on regional economies over the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","118401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802982","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>The UK has a strong record on reduction of nuclear weapons – since 2010 we have reduced the number of operationally available warheads to no more than 120, and remain committed to reducing our stockpile of nuclear warheads to no more than 180 by the mid-2020s. However, we note with concern that a number of states continue to produce fissile material for nuclear weapons outside the Non Proliferation Treaty. In particular, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea's (DPRK) nuclear and ballistic missile programmes pose an unacceptable threat to the international community and we are working closely with our international partners to exert maximum political and economic pressure on the DPRK to change its direction. The UK remains committed to the Iran nuclear deal, which marks a major step forward in preventing Iran from developing a nuclear weapons capability.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-13T17:08:23.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802982/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802982/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-08","Nuclear Weapons: Proliferation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of progress internationally on the non-proliferation and reduction of nuclear weapons; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","118402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802983","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-13","<p>Government’s sport strategy ‘Sporting Future’, published in December 2015, noted that just 5.5% of elite coaches were from Black and Minority Ethnic (BAME) backgrounds, demonstrating that high performance coaching was not drawing its talent from the widest pool available. It commissioned UK Sport to review what steps could be taken to remove barriers to minority groups (and women) progressing into high performance coaching roles with a view to diversifying the talent pool and ultimately improving overall performance.</p><p> </p><p>UK Sport has since put a number of activities and processes in place to help increase the number of high quality opportunities for BAME coaches. For example their Elite Coaching Team works with role models to encourage other coaches to apply for relevant roles, and they work with Sporting Equals on data relating to BAME people, which forms part of the Sporting Equals' Leaderboard National Steering Group. One of the aims of this group is to develop and share toolkits that sports can use to help diversify their recruitment, and in particular recruit more BAME staff. UK Sport also use results from the sport-wide Culture Health Check to analyse emerging trends around equality and diversity issues, and they work closely with the Sports Councils’ Equity Group with Home Country Sports Councils to develop consistent approaches to equality and opportunities with national governing bodies.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-12-13T10:11:36.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802983/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802983/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-08","Football: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps are being taken to ensure that BAME coaches experience adequate opportunities in sports that operate under the UK Sports umbrella.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","118403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802984","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>The Government engages regularly with new nuclear build developers on their supply chain plans as we seek to maximise UK economic benefit; this includes fuel manufacturing. The Government is also actively involved in advising and supporting UK companies who are pursuing nuclear fuel supply and manufacturing opportunities in overseas markets.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-13T16:01:38.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802984/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802984/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Nuclear Fuels: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support the nuclear fuel manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802985","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Sourcing of fuel for new nuclear power stations is a matter for the project developers. The Government engages regularly with the developers on their supply chain plans as we seek to maximise UK economic benefit arising from the projects; this includes fuel manufacturing.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-13T16:02:50.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802985/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802985/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Nuclear Fuels: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that nuclear fuel for the Moorside nuclear reactors is manufactured in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802986","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Sourcing of fuel for new nuclear power stations is a matter for the project developers. The Government engages regularly with the developers on their supply chain plans as we seek to maximise UK economic benefit arising from the projects; this includes fuel manufacturing.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-13T16:07:05.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802986/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802986/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Nuclear Fuels: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has any plans to ensure that nuclear fuel for the nuclear reactors at (a) Hinkley Point C, (b) Bradwell B and (c) Wylfa Newydd is manufactured in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802987","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Toshiba, rather than the Department, has selected KEPCO as their preferred bidder to buy Nugen and we will engage with the companies to understand their proposals for the Moorside project.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-13T11:12:21.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802987/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802987/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Nuclear Power Stations: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what effect his Department’s decision to select the Korea Electric Power Corporation as the preferred bidder to take over building the Moorside nuclear reactors has had on the date the Moorside nuclear plant is projected to be (a) completed and (b) operational.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802988","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>Any nuclear vendor wishing to deploy their reactor technology in the UK is required to comply with the UK’s regulatory and licensing requirements, and must successfully complete a Generic Design Assessment. Toshiba recently awarded Korea Electric Power Corporation (KEPCO) preferred bidder status for acquiring Nugen and further commercial decisions would be required before any regulatory processes could begin.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T11:49:41.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802988/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802988/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Korea Electric Power Corporation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Korea Electric Power Corporation currently holds a licence to manufacture nuclear reactors in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802989","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>Nugen’s published plans under Toshiba were to deploy three AP1000 reactors, each designed to produce a net power output of 1117 Megawatts. Now Toshiba has awarded Korea Electric Power Corporation preferred bidder status for acquiring Nugen, we will engage the companies to understand their proposals for the Moorside project.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T11:50:43.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802989/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802989/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Nuclear Power Stations: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what comparative assessment he has made of the anticipated total output of the entire Moorside nuclear plant utilising the Westinghouse AP1000 nuclear reactor design and the Korea Electric Power Corporation APR-1400 nuclear reactor design.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","118409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802990","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-12-13","<p>As part of our work preparing to make a success of our departure from the European Union, we are carrying out a broad range of sectoral analysis as you would expect a responsible Government to do. This includes analysis of sectors across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is engaging extensively with the Welsh Government, along with Welsh organisations and institutions and in order to secure a deal that works in the interests of not just Wales, but the whole of the United Kingdom. We look forward to further engagement with all the Devolved Administrations, including on any additional analysis they have produced.</p><p> </p><p>As we move into the second phase of negotiations we are confident of agreeing a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement with the EU. Securing a future partnership between the UK and EU is in the interests of both sides, so we approach these negotiations anticipating success. We do not want or expect an outcome where no trade agreement is agreed.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-12-13T17:59:47.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802990/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802990/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-12-08","Exports: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on Welsh exports to the EU of the UK not having a trade agreement with the EU when the UK leaves the EU.","true","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","118410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802991","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-12-18","<p>As part of our work preparing to make a success of our departure from the European Union, we are carrying out a broad range of sectoral analysis, as you would expect a responsible Government to do. Our sector report on Agriculture covers: a detailed description of the sector; the current EU regulatory regime and a summary of sector views. The report has been made available for members of both Houses to read in a secure reading room.</p><p>The Government’s Agriculture Bill will enable us to support a thriving and self-reliant farming sector that is more competitive, productive and profitable; to protect our precious natural environment for future generations; and to deliver on the manifesto commitment to provide stability for farmers as we exit the EU.</p><p>We are committed to getting the best possible deal for the United Kingdom - a deal that works for all sectors of the UK economy. We believe that a future partnership deal is in the interests of both sides, so we approach these negotiations anticipating success. We do not want or expect an outcome where no trade agreement is agreed.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-12-18T17:05:05.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802991/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802991/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-12-08","Agriculture: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on agricultural trade with the EU of the UK not having a trade agreement with the EU when the UK leaves the EU.","true","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","118411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802992","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Welsh Government administers payments and provides rural development support to Welsh farmers. Therefore this is a matter for the devolved administration.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-18T15:51:51.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802992/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802992/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-08","Agriculture: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of Welsh farmers receive direct payments and rural development support.","true","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","118412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802993","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-13","<p>The Government has pledged to continue to commit the same cash total in funds for farm support until the end of this Parliament, expected in 2022. This provides a greater level of security and certainty for farmers and landowners than anywhere else in the EU, where funding is guaranteed only until 2020.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-13T18:08:02.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802993/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802993/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-08","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to match existing levels of Common Agricultural Policy funding after the UK leaves the EU.","true","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","118413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802994","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-13","<p>Sections 68 and 70 of the Equality Act 2010 confirm the right of assistance dog owners to travel by taxi or private hire vehicle free from the fear of discrimination.</p><p> </p><p>The Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (Taxis) (Carrying of Guide Dogs etc) (England and Wales) Regulations 2000 and the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (Private Hire Vehicles) (Carriage of Guide Dogs etc) (England and Wales) Regulations 2003 specify the form of exemption notices displayed by taxsi and private hire vehicle drivers who are medically unfit to fulfil the related duties.</p><p>I understand that it can be difficult for visually impaired people to identify genuine exemption notices presented to them, and officials have discussed with the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association alternative options, including the provision by licensing authorities of an additional non-statutory notice in Braille and large print.</p><p> </p><p>We currently have no plans to amend Regulations.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-13T16:59:16.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802994/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802994/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-08","Taxis: Guide Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will amend the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (Taxis) (Carrying of Guide Dogs etc) (England and Wales) Regulations 2000 and the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (Private Hire Vehicles) (Carriage of Guide Dogs etc) (England and Wales) Regulations 2003 to enable notices of exemption to be displayed in large print or with tactile features incorporated.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","118414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802995","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-13","<p>I refer the Hon Member for Hemsworth to my answer of 30th October 2017 UIN 109650.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-13T15:52:29.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802995/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802995/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish a response to the consultation on the location of the Rolling Stock Depot for the Yorkshire leg of the High Speed 2 route.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","118415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802996","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>I was not aware on 24 October of the allegations subsequently made by the Panorama programme. HMG is not aware of any evidence of UK funding directly fallling into the hands of terrorist groups through the Access to Justice and Community Services programme in Syria.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-13T17:10:19.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802996/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802996/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-08","Syria: Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Rt. Hon. Alastair Burt, was aware that money from the Access to Justice and Community Services programme in Syria had fallen into the hands of terrorists when he responded to a question in the Chamber by the Rt. Hon. Emily Thornberry on 24 October 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","118416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802997","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>All FCO ODA expenditure conforms to the department's robust management and assurance processes to ensure it delivers value for money for the UK taxpayer. This includes following the processes for monitoring expenditure, as laid out in Her Majesty's Treasury's document, 'UK Official Development Assistance: value for money guidance'. Any allegations of fraud are swiftly investigated and if substantiated projects will be terminated.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-13T17:12:10.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802997/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802997/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-08","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps he has taken to improve the transparency, effectiveness, and fraud prevention of Official Development Assistance spending by his Department.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","118417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802998","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has not awarded any new contracts to Adam Smith International (ASI) this Financial Year. However, like the Department for International Development (DFID), the FCO is continuing to work with ASI on high priority existing projects.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-13T17:13:35.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802998/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802998/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-08","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Adam Smith International","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 6 September 2017 to Question 9083, what assessment he made of the potential merits of freezing funding to Adam Smith International in February 2017, in line with the decision taken by the Department for International Development.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","118418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802999","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Right to Contest already provides a mechanism by which local people can challenge public bodies, including local councils, to release unused and underused land for housing.</p><p>The Government has no current plans to change this approach but would give consideration to any specific proposals which come forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-18T12:01:11.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802999/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802999/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802999/answer/previousversion/29543","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-08","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to introduce a right to bid for assets held by local authorities to release land for housing.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","118419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803000","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-13","<p>Revenue Support Grant is an unringfenced grant allocated as part of the Local Government Finance Settlement. Along with council tax, retained business rates and other sources of income, it funds core services provided by councils, including social care, road repairs and waste services.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-13T16:19:37.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803000/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803000/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-08","Housing: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding from the Revenue Support Grant (RSG) was allocated to (a) Hull City Council and (b) England to cover costs related to student accommodation; how many student households were covered by the RSG; and what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of student-occupied properties that were covered by the RSG for each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","118420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803001","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>All Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) funded programmes managed by the FCO have robust monitoring processes in place to mitigate the risk of funds being diverted. We take appropriate action on all allegations of misuse of funds. Where specific human rights concerns are identified, an Overseas Security and Justice Assessment is completed to identify risks and mitigating actions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-13T13:27:40.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803001/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803001/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-08","Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that projects led by his Department and funded through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund do not contribute to human rights violations or enable funding to be diverted to terrorist groups.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","118421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803002","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>Competition investigations into mergers are a matter for the independent Competition and Markets Authority.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-13T15:46:18.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803002/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803002/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-08","Tesco: Booker Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the proposed merger of Tesco and Booker wholesale, what representations he has received on the potential of a price advantage being gained by for Booker in the wholesale food sector.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","118422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803003","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>The data on the Government Grants Information System is not sufficiently robust to provide a comprehensive picture of total funding to organisations with a charity number for the Financial Years 2014/15 and 2015/16. This is because we did not begin collecting award level data until 2015/16. From 2016/17 departments are required to record charity numbers against all applicable grants, this will improve the dataset for future years.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","118424","2017-12-13T14:35:49.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803003/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803003/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-08","Charities: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Government grants were allocated to organisations with a UK charity number in (a) 2014-2015 and (b) 2015-2016; and what  the total value was of those grants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","118423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803004","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>The data on the Government Grants Information System is not sufficiently robust to provide a comprehensive picture of total funding to organisations with a charity number for the Financial Years 2014/15 and 2015/16. This is because we did not begin collecting award level data until 2015/16. From 2016/17 departments are required to record charity numbers against all applicable grants, this will improve the dataset for future years.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","118423","2017-12-13T14:35:49.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803004/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803004/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-08","Charities: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Government grants were allocated to organisations with a UK charity number in (a) 2014-2015 and (b) 2015-2016, and what the total value of those grants was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","118424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803005","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Government’s planning policy for airfields is set out in the National Planning Policy Framework. This is supported by our planning practice guidance on <em>'Transport evidence bases in plan-making and decision taking’</em>, which makes clear to local authorities that they should consider the interconnectivity between airfields of different sizes and that they should have regard to the Aviation Policy Framework.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-18T11:58:38.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803005/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803005/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-08","Aviation: Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to introduce sector-led planning guidance for general aviation airfields; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","118425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803006","Home Office","false","2018-01-17","<p>EU citizens and their family members who obtain settled status under the Withdrawal Agreement (WA) will be granted Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR). This status will provide the holder with the same rights and access to benefits, education and healthcare as those who obtained it under the Immigration Rules before the UK joined the EU</p><p>In addition, the UK and the European Commission have agreed that those granted settled status under the WA will also benefit from certain more favourable entitlements including, for example, that ILR will not lapse unless the holder has been continuously absent from the UK for over five years, as opposed to two years; and more generous provisions relating to future family reunification.</p><p>Further details of the agreement with the European Commission can be found in ‘Joint report on progress during phase 1 of negotiations under Article 50 TEU on the United Kingdom’s orderly withdrawal from the European Union’ published on 8 December 2017, available here: <br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/joint-report-on-progress-during-phase-1-of-negotiations-under-article-50-teu-on-the-uks-orderly-withdrawal-from-the-eu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/joint-report-on-progress-during-phase-1-of-negotiations-under-article-50-teu-on-the-uks-orderly-withdrawal-from-the-eu</a>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-17T13:03:22.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803006/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803006/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-08","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the differences are between the proposed settled status for EU nationals after the UK leaves the EU and the current status of EU citizens who obtained indefinite leave to remain before the UK joined the EU.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","118426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803007","Department of Health","false","2017-12-13","<p>No research on the effects of drug use disorders on Disability-Adjusted Life Years lost in each region of England has been commissioned by the Department, the National Health Service or Public Heath England in the last seven years.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-13T15:35:55.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803007/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803007/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 December to Question 117339 on Drugs: Misuse, what research has been commission on  the effect of drug use disorders on Disability-Adjusted Life Years lost in each region of England by (a) his Department, (b) the NHS, and (c) Public Health England in each of the last 7 years; and whether such data is shared with the Institute of Health Metrics and Evaluation.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","118427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803008","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-13","<p>This level of detail is not requested on VAT returns and therefore we do not have data available on how much revenue is raised from VAT on phone charges for making donations to charities. There is no VAT on the donations.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-13T16:55:17.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803008/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803008/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-08","Charitable Donations: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount accrued to the public purse from VAT on phone-call donations to charity in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","118428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803019","Department of Health","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) recently updated the evidence on folic acid in response to a request from Food Standards Scotland and reiterated its support for mandatory folic acid fortification of United Kingdom flour, provided that this is introduced alongside restrictions on voluntary fortification of foods with folic acid. Ministers are currently considering SACN’s recommendations on mandatory fortification.</p><p> </p><p>Neural tube defects (NTDs) are a serious issue. To help those who may have inadequate folate levels through their diet, the Department provides general advice and health education messages in a range of settings targeted at women of childbearing age to encourage the use of folic acid supplements both pre- and post-conception. Information is also available online via NHS Choices including advice on seeing a healthcare professional as early in pregnancy as possible and that women should take 400 micrograms of folic acid every day prior to conception, and in the first 12 weeks of pregnancy, to help prevent NTDs.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL3985 ; HL3986","2017-12-20T13:50:02.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803019/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803019/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Flour: Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the feasibility of introducing mandatory fortification of flour with folic acid, following recommendations from the Food Standards Agency and the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL3984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803020","Department of Health","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) recently updated the evidence on folic acid in response to a request from Food Standards Scotland and reiterated its support for mandatory folic acid fortification of United Kingdom flour, provided that this is introduced alongside restrictions on voluntary fortification of foods with folic acid. Ministers are currently considering SACN’s recommendations on mandatory fortification.</p><p> </p><p>Neural tube defects (NTDs) are a serious issue. To help those who may have inadequate folate levels through their diet, the Department provides general advice and health education messages in a range of settings targeted at women of childbearing age to encourage the use of folic acid supplements both pre- and post-conception. Information is also available online via NHS Choices including advice on seeing a healthcare professional as early in pregnancy as possible and that women should take 400 micrograms of folic acid every day prior to conception, and in the first 12 weeks of pregnancy, to help prevent NTDs.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL3984 ; HL3986","2017-12-20T13:50:02.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803020/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803020/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Flour: Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that the fortification of flour with folic acid could have prevented approximately 2,000 cases of serious neural tube birth defects in the UK since 1998.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL3985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803021","Department of Health","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) recently updated the evidence on folic acid in response to a request from Food Standards Scotland and reiterated its support for mandatory folic acid fortification of United Kingdom flour, provided that this is introduced alongside restrictions on voluntary fortification of foods with folic acid. Ministers are currently considering SACN’s recommendations on mandatory fortification.</p><p> </p><p>Neural tube defects (NTDs) are a serious issue. To help those who may have inadequate folate levels through their diet, the Department provides general advice and health education messages in a range of settings targeted at women of childbearing age to encourage the use of folic acid supplements both pre- and post-conception. Information is also available online via NHS Choices including advice on seeing a healthcare professional as early in pregnancy as possible and that women should take 400 micrograms of folic acid every day prior to conception, and in the first 12 weeks of pregnancy, to help prevent NTDs.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL3984 ; HL3985","2017-12-20T13:50:02.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803021/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/803021/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-08","Flour: Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government following the joint letter from the Scottish Government’s Minister for Public Health and Sport and the Welsh Government’s Cabinet Secretary for Health and Social Services to the Secretary of State for Health on 1 December, whether they have any plans to introduce mandatory fortification of flour with folic acid on a UK-wide basis to help reduce neural tube defects in unborn babies.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe"